7","1492":"1492","1548":"1548","Norwich, City of Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cocke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Alcock","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Alcok</i>, a pet form of any of the many medieval personal names beginning with <i>Al-</i>, especially <i>Alan</i> and <i>Alexander</i>. The Middle English hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i> (see   Cocke  ) was very commonly added to personal names in Middle English: compare for example   Hancock   and   Wilcock  ."]},{"name":"Cockman","meanings":["English: occupational name, from either   Cocke   + <i>man</i> ‘Cock's servant’, or else from Middle English <i>cok(e)</i> + <i>man</i> ‘cook's assistant or servant’."]},{"name":"Cook","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."]},{"name":"Cockrell","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French, Middle English <i>cokerel</i> ‘young cock’ (see   Cocke  )."]},{"name":"Cocklin","meanings":["English: from an Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cokelin</i>, a French double diminutive of   Cocke   2.","Perhaps also an Americanized form of Swiss German and South German <b>Köchlin</b>, <b>Koechlin</b>, or <b>Köchling</b>, all diminutives of   Koch  ."]},{"name":"Cox","meanings":["English: variant of   Cocke   and   Cook  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish (Ulster): mistranslation of <b>Mac Con Coille</b> (‘son of <i>Cú Choille</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the wood’), as if formed with <i>coileach</i> ‘cock, rooster’.","Dutch and Flemish: genitivized patronymic from the personal name <i>Cock</i>, a vernacular short form of   Cornelius  ."]},{"name":"Cocking","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Cocking in Sussex. The placename denoted ‘(the settlement of) Cocking's people’, from the Old English personal name <i>Cocca</i> + the group-name suffix <i>-ingas</i>.","patronymic from either of two Middle English personal names, <i>Cok(k)ing</i> (Old English <i>Coccing</i>) or <i>Cokin</i> (probably Old French in origin), both of which are pet forms of   Cocke   2."]},{"name":"Bulcock","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bule</i>, <i>bole</i> ‘bull’ + the diminutive suffix <i>-cock</i> (see   Cocke  ). Compare   Bocock  ."]},{"name":"Coxon","meanings":["English: patronymic from <i>Cock</i> (an affectionate term of address; see   Cocke  ) or the surname   Cox  , with the addition of <i>son</i> ‘son’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Cocke was born in 1466, in Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Martha Hais."},"et":{"1466–":"1466–Surnud","1477–Female":"1477–Surnud","1492–1548":"1492–1548","–Male":"Surnud","1466–Male":"1466–Surnud","1466":"1466","1477":"1477","1492":"1492","1548":"1548","Norwich, City of Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1466–":"1466–Kuollut","1477–Female":"1477–Kuollut","1492–1548":"1492–1548","–Male":"Kuollut","1466–Male":"1466–Kuollut","1466":"1466","1477":"1477","1492":"1492","1548":"1548","Norwich, City of Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1466–":"1466–Décédé","1477–Female":"1477–Décédée","1492–1548":"1492–1548","–Male":"Décédé","1466–Male":"1466–Décédé","1466":"1466","1477":"1477","1492":"1492","1548":"1548","Norwich, City of Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Thomas Cocke est né en 1466, à Norwich, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille avec Martha Hais."},"de":{"1466–":"1466–Verstorben","1477–Female":"1477–Verstorben","1492–1548":"1492–1548","–Male":"Verstorben","1466–Male":"1466–Verstorben","1466":"1466","1477":"1477","1492":"1492","1548":"1548","Norwich, City of Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Thomas Cocke wurde 1466 in Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mit Martha Hais mindestens 1 Sohn und 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1466–":"1466–Desede","1477–Female":"1477–Desede","1492–1548":